Price Prediction Challenge¶

In this project, you are given a dataset of real-estate properties, and we ask you to develop code that predicts the list price of a property. You should have in mind that the price of each property may change a lot given its region, and your solution should take that into account (try some feature engineering).

For the solution, we request that you build at least 2 models for price prediction, and after evaluating each model, you should compare them to choose the best one for the task (use the mean absolute percentage error for comparison).

Step by Step¶

  • Understanding the dataset
  • Filter the dataset, remove unused, inconsistent and outliers values.
  • Visualizing the dataset
  • Choose 4 models from different categories (Machine Learning)
  • Evaluation of models
  • Conclusion

Undestend dataset¶

Dataset Description

  • The dataset is extracted from a real world real-estate database and its features are respectively:
  • apn : identification code for a given property.
  • zip_code : area code of a given property.
  • property_type : type of the property; consider only the properties with property_type = residential
  • lot : area of the lot
  • sqft : square footage.
  • beds : number of bedrooms
  • baths : number of bathrooms, this value can be a float, because there are 3 types of bathrooms, each one represented by 0.5, 0.75 and 1.0, and this feature is the sum of these values.
  • price : price of property.

Filter the dataset, remove unused, inconsistent and outliers values.¶

Filter only residential register type and drop unecessary columns

In [7]:
# filter only residential
df = df[df['property_type'] == 'residential']

# drop unnecessary columns, these columns won't be useful in analysis and prediction
df = df.drop(['apn','property_type'], axis=1)

Remove registers sqft and price with zero values. Remove zip_code empty too.

In [8]:
# Not necessery remove 'lot', because this value will not be used. Low correlation
#df = df[df['lot'] > 0.1]

# remove sqft zero
df = df[df['sqft'] > 0.1]

# remove price zero
df = df[df['price'] > 0.1]

# Remove residential with zipcode null
df = df[df['zip_code'].notnull()]

# Converto all to float
df['beds'] = df['beds'].astype(float)
df['price'] = df['price'].astype(float)

Remove outliers values, values with greater than 3x standard deviation. This process is useful for removing values out of the analysis, avoiding negative effects. It may be typing error or even unusual values

In [9]:
for var in ['baths', 'beds', 'sqft', 'price']:
    df = df[df[var] < df[var].mean()+3*df[var].std()]

Converts postal code to coordinate latitude and longitude¶

In [10]:
# Zip codes
df_zip = pd.read_csv("zipcod_to_cord.txt")

def zipcode_to_lat_lng(zipcode):
    zipnum = int(zipcode.split("-")[0])
    line = df_zip[df_zip['ZIP'] == zipnum]
    if len(line) > 0:
        return [line.LAT.values[0], line.LNG.values[0]]
    else:
        return [None, None]

This process may take a few minutes because it uses a webservice, but only runs once. Do not need to use it if it were in production, data would already be available

In [11]:
df['lat'] = df['zip_code'].apply(lambda x: zipcode_to_lat_lng(x)[0])
df['lng'] = df['zip_code'].apply(lambda x: zipcode_to_lat_lng(x)[1])

Conclusion¶

The model that presented the best result was the RandoFlorest, mainly because it is an ensable and can be treated as a model of regions, very useful to map the nonlinearity presented by latitude and longitude coordinates. Knn also presented satisfactory results by the same principle. The worst model was the liner, it is clear that the relationship is non-linear, so a linear regression would never fit well to the data, it is possible to see the trend of the linear model by the residue report, to underestimate the price values.

Either way, a coefficient of determination of 80% for RandomForest is an acceptable result. But it is clear that the model still needs to be improved with other independent variables.
